    <div style="margin-top: 0;">
      Hi Emil,
    </div>    <p style="margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em;">This is our last thought of this series. We hope you got an idea of how you can use Capacities for your work and hope you like it. We want to leave you with some <strong style="color: var(--tw-prose-bold); font-weight: 600;">advice</strong> on how to make building a <strong style="color: var(--tw-prose-bold); font-weight: 600;">Studio for Your Mind</strong> simple yet effective.</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal; margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em; padding-left: 1.5555556em;">
<li style="margin-top: 0.6666667em; margin-bottom: 0.6666667em; padding-left: 0.4444444em;">
<p style="margin-bottom: 1.3333333em; margin-top: 1.3333333em;"><strong style="color: var(--tw-prose-bold); font-weight: 600;">Start with pages, images, and web links. Don't over-optimize.</strong></p>
<p style="margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em;">Capacities already provides basic content types. Use them, create notes, add media, tag your content with general keywords that relate to your work.</p>
</li>
<li style="margin-top: 0.6666667em; margin-bottom: 0.6666667em; padding-left: 0.4444444em;">
<p style="margin-bottom: 1.3333333em; margin-top: 1.3333333em;"><strong style="color: var(--tw-prose-bold); font-weight: 600;">Refine your tagging over time</strong></p>
<p style="margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em;">For example, you might realize that the tag &quot;philosophy&quot; is too general. Start refining your tags to make them more granular and project-oriented. An excellent article on tagging can be found on the <a href="https://fortelabs.com/blog/a-complete-guide-to-tagging-for-personal-knowledge-management/" style="color: var(--tw-prose-links); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 500">Forte Labs blog</a>.</p>
</li>
<li style="margin-top: 0.6666667em; margin-bottom: 0.6666667em; padding-left: 0.4444444em;">
<p style="margin-bottom: 1.3333333em; margin-top: 1.3333333em;"><strong style="color: var(--tw-prose-bold); font-weight: 600;">If you find patterns, create your own object types.</strong></p>
<p style="margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em;">After a while, you might realize that you need more structure. You can now introduce <a href="https://capacities.io/content-types" style="color: var(--tw-prose-links); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 500">object types</a> to your studio. Create a book type with an author field, rating, and other properties and <a href="https://docs.capacities.io/reference/content-types#type-conversions" style="color: var(--tw-prose-links); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 500">turn your book pages into books</a>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p style="margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em;">It's important not to try creating a structure that works forever before you even start –  that's something we're doing in a world of folders. Create your thoughts and adjust your system over time. You will never know everything before you start. And the great thing: That's where the flexible structure of Capacities shines. Reorganizing is as simple as adding new tags and changing the content type of your notes.</p>
<p style="margin-top: 1.3333333em; margin-bottom: 1.3333333em;">If you want to learn more, we recommend <a href="https://docs.capacities.io" style="color: var(--tw-prose-links); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 500">browsing our documentation</a> or <a href="https://discord.gg/3eBP9YxHgQ" style="color: var(--tw-prose-links); text-decoration: underline; font-weight: 500">joining our community</a> to exchange ideas with like-minded people. It's a great place to learn and get inspired.</p>    <table role="presentation" border="0" width="100%" style="width: 100%; table-layout: auto; text-align: left; margin-top: 2em; font-size: 0.8888889em; line-height: 1.5; margin-bottom: 0; max-width: 536px;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
